Test Document 1: D-59041 

Foreword : African-American Male, 51 years of age. Imprisoned for tax evasion. Grandmother expired 2 weeks prior to the video log's recording. Notified the day of testing.

Procedure:  D-59041 was instructed to listen to SCP-4184, then told to write about his favorite sport.
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

 

 Junior Researcher Swalls:  Er, D-59041?

 D-59041:  Why the fuck am I here?

Junior Researcher Swalls:  Well, we just want you to listen to some music, then write a bit. About anything, like a little journal.

 D-59041:  Seems useless.

Junior Researcher Swalls:  No. No it is not. It's slow, classical music.

 D-59041:  You trying to make me cry, or something? Shit's not gonna work.

 Junior Researcher Swalls:  Well, I guess we'll see.

(Junior Researcher Swalls exits the room, as SCP-4184 begins to play.)

D-59041:  You know what, lab coats? I fucking told y'all this wasn't gonna work. You guys trying to make me sad with Van Gogh, or something?

D-59041:  Fucking assholes.

D-59041:  What'll it take for you to get me out of here? Money? I got a whole lot of that. You need rides? Jobs? I can call someone, if you guys give me a phone.

D-59041:  (Quiet sobbing can be heard.)

D-59041:  Alright, just give me the damn paper. Let me write.

(SCP-4184's playing ceases. D-59041 is given a piece of paper, and a pen. Document is attached below.)
附加记录：    





Grandmama, are you out there? It's me, your Bill. It's been a long time since I talked to you, Grandmama, but for taking taking it a bit too far. I remember those nights where you used to make me lemonade, sit me down, and tell me about Dad, tell me jokes, tell me stories. Oh, the fun we used to have. I remember when you used to tuck me in at night. But, when I grew older… I guess I thought that I didn't need that anymore. So I suppose that’s why I stopped talking to you and Pops. And, we didn’t end up talking for a long, long while after that. And that’s probably why I ended up where I am now. I had a family. No matter now. I went to jail, Grandmama, and Dad and Mom don’t even visit anymore. As lonely as I may be, Grandmama, I still love you, and I know if you knew where I was, you’d come visit too. You always did try to, because you loved me too.




